{{Infobox scientist | honorific_prefix = | name = Andrew Paul Guinand | honorific_suffix = | native_name = | native_name_lang = | image = | image_size = | alt = | caption = | birth_date = {{birth date |1912|03|3}} | birth_place = | death_date = {{death date and age |1987|03|22 |1912|03|3}} | death_place = | death_cause = | resting_place = | resting_place_coordinates = | other_names = Andrew Guinand | residence = | citizenship = [[Australia]]n<!--source?--> | nationality = | fields = Mathematics<!--source?--> | workplaces = [[University of New England (Australia)|University of New England]], Australia | patrons = | education = | alma_mater = | thesis_title = | thesis_url = | thesis_year = | doctoral_advisor = | academic_advisors = | doctoral_students = | notable_students = | known_for = | influences = | influenced = | awards = | author_abbrev_bot = | author_abbrev_zoo = | spouse = | partner = | children = | signature = | signature_alt = | website = | footnotes = }} '''Andrew Paul Guinand''' (known as '''Andrew Guinand'''), {{nowrap|(1912 - 1987)}} was an Australian mathematician and a professor at the [[University of New England (Australia)|University of New England]].<ref name=guibio>{{cite web|date=1997 |author=J J O'Connor and E F Robertson |title=Andrew Paul Guinand |publisher=MacTutor |accessdate=2016-01-30 |url=http://www-history.mcs.st-andrews.ac.uk/Biographies/Guinand.html }}</ref>
== Early life and education == Guinand attended [[St Peter's College, Adelaide<!--correct one?-->|St Peter's College]], [[Adelaide]] from 1924 to 1929. In 1930, he entered [[St. Mark's College (University of Adelaide)|St Mark's College]] of the [[University of Adelaide]] to study mathematics. After graduating in 1933, Guinand attended the [[University of Oxford]] on a [[Rhodes Scholarship]], where [[Edward Charles Titchmarsh]] supervised his doctoral research.<ref name="guibio" /><ref>{{MathGenealogy|id=14696}}</ref> From 1937 to 1938, he studied at [[Göttingen]], after which he studied at [[Princeton University]], until in 1940 he joined the [[Royal Canadian Air Force]] and served as a navigator.<ref name=guibio/>
Guinand worked as an assistant at the [[University of Cambridge]], and then as a lecturer at the [[Defence College of Management and Technology|Royal Military College of Science]], where he was eventually promoted to [[Associate professor]] of Mathematics. In 1955, he was named Head of Department at the [[University of New England (Australia)|University of New England]] at [[Armidale, New South Wales|Armidale]].<ref name=guibio/> After two years at Armidale, he moved to the [[University of Alberta]] in [[Edmonton|Edmonton, Alberta]], and in 1960 moved again to the [[University of Saskatchewan]]. In 1964, he moved once more, becoming the first chairman of the mathematics department at [[Trent University]] which had been founded the previous year.<ref name=guibio/>
== Work == Guinand's research included work in [[number theory]] (particularly [[prime number]]s and the [[Riemann hypothesis]]), as well as generalizations of the [[Fourier transform]], in addition to publications on assorted topics including air navigation and the computation of [[pi]].<ref name=guibio/><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Guinand|first=A. P.|date=1945|title=An Asymptotic Series for Computing π|journal=[[The Mathematical Gazette]]|volume=29|issue=287|pages=214–218|doi=10.2307/3609261|via=|jstor=3609261}}</ref>
In 1959, he published a paper on the [[Poisson summation formula]] for which he presented a simpler solution.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Guinand|first=A. P.|date=1960|title=Some Finite Identities Connected with Poisson's Summation Formula|url=https://www.cambridge.org/core/journals/proceedings-of-the-edinburgh-mathematical-society/article/some-finite-identities-connected-with-poissons-summation-formula/FFD315A1A791FB843E237153D2BB2844|journal=[[Proceedings of the Edinburgh Mathematical Society]]|volume=12|issue=1|pages=17–25|doi=10.1017/s0013091500025001|issn=1464-3839|via=}}</ref><ref name="pr">{{Citation|title=Analytic Number Theory An Introduction|date=1980<!--earlier?-->|url=https://archive.org/stream/AnalyticalNumberTheoryAnIntroduction/Bellman-AnalyticalNumberTheory_djvu.txt|publication-date=1980|quote=|author=[[Richard E. Bellman]]|pages=92|publisher=The Benjamin/ Cummings Publishing Company, Inc.|isbn=0-8053-0360-X|accessdate=2016-03-26}} (HTML 117 kB)</ref> Guinand's work on this problem was largely forgotten and remained in obscurity until it was re-discovered by [[Yves Meyer]] in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://phys.org/news/2016-03-mathematician-solution-poisson-formula-problem.html|title=Mathematician finds his 'new' solution to Poisson formula problem buried in 1959 paper|last=Zyga|first=Lisa|date=2016-03-25|website=[[Phys.org]]|publisher=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|accessdate=2016-03-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Meyer|first=Yves F.|date=2016-03-22|title=Measures with locally finite support and spectrum|url=http://www.pnas.org/content/113/12/3152|journal=[[Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences]]|language=en|volume=113|issue=12|pages=3152–3158|doi=10.1073/pnas.1600685113|issn=0027-8424|pmid=26929358|via=|pmc=4812708}}</ref>
== External links == * [https://mathoverflow.net/questions/234543/have-the-explicit-poisson-type-formulas-of-guinand-and-meyer-been-observed-befor mathoverflow.net: Have the explicit Poisson-type formulas of Guinand and Meyer been observed before?] (2016-03-26)
